  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">Got Questions?</span>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <p>Common questions about NRI home loans.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            Can an NRI buy property in India?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              Yes, under FEMA regulations, NRIs and PIOs/OCIs can freely purchase residential and commercial property in India. There is no limit on the number of properties. However, NRIs cannot purchase agricultural land, plantation property, or farmhouse. Payment must be made through NRE/NRO account or via normal banking channels from abroad. TrueCred ensures full FEMA compliance in your transaction.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            Can I apply for an NRI home loan from abroad?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              Yes, the entire application process can be completed from abroad. You can submit documents digitally, do video KYC, and sign loan agreements via power of attorney. Banks have NRI home loan cells that operate across time zones. You may need to visit India only for property registration in some states. TrueCred's NRI desk coordinates with you at convenient times based on your time zone.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            How can I repay my NRI home loan?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              NRI home loan EMIs can be paid through: (a) NRE account — funds from overseas income credited to NRE account (tax-free in India), (b) NRO account — from rental income or other Indian income, (c) Direct remittance from overseas bank account, or (d) Post-dated cheques from NRE/NRO account. Setting up a standing instruction from your NRE account is the most popular and convenient method.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            What are the tax benefits for NRIs on home loans?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              NRIs get the same tax benefits as resident Indians: Section 24(b) deduction up to ₹2 lakhs on interest for self-occupied property, Section 80C deduction up to ₹1.5 lakhs on principal repayment, and additional deduction under Section 80EEA for affordable housing. Note that rental income from Indian property is taxable in India but may be eligible for DTAA benefits to avoid double taxation in your country of residence.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            What is the loan-to-value ratio for NRI home loans?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              NRI home loans typically offer LTV of 75-85% depending on the loan amount and lender. For loans up to ₹30 lakhs, LTV can be up to 85%; for ₹30-75 lakhs, up to 80%; and above ₹75 lakhs, up to 75%. The remaining amount must be funded from your own sources (NRE/NRO funds). Some banks may offer higher LTV for NRIs working in low-risk countries like USA, UK, or Singapore.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

